What Does Lead Qualification Actually Look Like in a PPL Program?
This is one of the most important questions B2B marketers ask when evaluating Pay-Per-Lead vendors. Qualification standards vary significantly across the industry, and a poorly qualified lead is not much better than no lead at all.

The BANT Framework and Beyond
Historically, lead qualification was framed around BANT: Budget, Authority, Need, and Timeline. While BANT remains a useful lens, modern B2B qualification goes deeper.

In 2026, high-quality PPL programs assess leads across multiple dimensions:

Firmographic Fit: Does the prospect's company match your target account profile in terms of industry, revenue band, employee count, and geography?

Persona Fit: Is the individual in a relevant job function and at the seniority level that influences or makes purchasing decisions?

Intent Signals: Has the prospect demonstrated active interest in a topic, technology, or solution category relevant to your offering? Intent data, drawn from first-party and third-party behavioral signals, is now a core component of quality lead qualification.

Engagement Quality: Did the prospect engage meaningfully with content, or did they simply click through without reading? Depth of engagement is an increasingly important quality signal.

At Intent Amplify, every lead we deliver goes through a rigorous qualification process that includes human validation in addition to AI-powered scoring. This hybrid approach ensures that what lands in your CRM is actionable, not just technically compliant.

What Questions Should You Ask a PPL Vendor?
Before committing to a Pay-Per-Lead program, ask your vendor the following:

How do you define a qualified lead for my specific ICP?

What data sources do you use to validate contact information?

How are intent signals captured and scored?

What is your replacement or guarantee policy for leads that do not meet agreed criteria?

How do you handle compliance with data privacy regulations like GDPR and CCPA?

The answers to these questions will tell you quickly whether a vendor has the infrastructure and accountability to deliver genuine value.

